hondo717: |cp||at|OK, now both the declarer and defenders would have done better had they paid better attention to the auction. One of the most common mistakes made by less experienced players during the play of the hand is to forget about the auction. You should always use the auction to provide you clues on how to play the hand. dee should count her tricks. She can count 5 hearts and 2 clubs for sure, assuming she believes roberta's 2 club bid  and she also knows kia is out of clubs. As dee has eight clubs between her and dummy, and roberta presumably has 5 for her overcall, that leaves none for kia.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at| 
hondo717: |cp||at|So, when dee plays her club at trick three,assuming she pulled trumps, she should finesse. Now, let us switch over to roberta. Once roberta gets in with her K of clubs at trick 7 she can count 5 tricks for sure for the defense, the 3 spades they already took, plus the K of clubs. The lead was fine roberta. It was the play at the end that could have been different. My point was, when roberta gets in with the K of clubs, that is the 4th trick for the defense. 2 spades, ruff, a club and ace of diamonds is fifth trick. In order to beat the hand roberta simply leads the 9 of clubs to dummy, and waits for her 2 diamond tricks.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT|^B@2|cp|8|at|
hondo717: |cp||at|Now, let me address whether dee should cue bid. There are two problems with a cue bid. First, dee only has 3 card support. I prefer that cue bids show 4 card support, although many people play you can cue bid with 3.  The second reason is dee's points are in clubs and roberta bid clubs. Therefore, I must be short in clubs, meaning the club length and cards are not a good fit with me. So I like 2@H rather than 3@C cue bid. And, as it turns out, we have trouble making 2@H as it is. With 3 trumps I bid a new suit and then raise after. Sometimes you cant do that, so you lie and cue bid with 3 card support.|
